## OOP Enforcement

All Python code must follow the four pillars of OOP:

1. Encapsulation: Use private/protected attributes (prefix with _ or __). Never access or modify object data directly — always use getter/setter methods or properties. Keep internal logic hidden from outside classes.

2. Abstraction: Expose only what's necessary through clean, simple interfaces. Complex logic should be handled internally within the class. Use abstract base classes (ABC) when defining shared interfaces across related classes.

3. Inheritance: Use parent classes to define shared behavior. Child classes should extend or specialize, not duplicate. Favor single inheritance and keep hierarchies shallow.

4. Polymorphism: Methods with the same name should behave appropriately for their class. Use method overriding in child classes. Write functions that operate on parent types so they work with any subclass.

General rules:
- Every major feature or entity (Coach, Athlete, Team, Workout, etc.) should be its own class.
- No loose functions floating outside of classes unless they are utility/helper functions.
- All classes must have a clear single responsibility.
- Use type hints on all method signatures.
- Include docstrings on every class and public method.

## Project Structure
- All routes go in app.py or separate blueprint files
- All HTML templates go in the templates/ folder
- All CSS, JS, and images go in the static/ folder
- Database models go in models.py
- Keep configuration in config.py

## Naming Conventions
- Files: lowercase with underscores (athlete_routes.py)
- Classes: PascalCase (AthleteProfile)
- Functions/variables: snake_case (get_roster)
- Templates: match their route name (roster.html for /roster)

## Code Quality
- No hardcoded values — use constants or config variables
- Add comments explaining why, not what
- Keep functions short — if it's over 30 lines, break it up
- Handle errors gracefully — no bare except blocks

## Git Workflow
- Pull before you start coding
- Commit often with clear messages
- Never push broken code to main

## Flask Specific
- Every route must have a docstring explaining what it does
- Use Flask blueprints if app.py gets over 150 lines
- All forms must validate input before touching the database
- Use flash messages for user feedback (success, errors)
- Keep database queries in models.py, not in routes

## Testing
- Critical features must have tests (login, database operations)
- Tests go in a tests/ folder at the project root
- Test files mirror the source file they test (test_models.py, test_app.py)
- Use descriptive test names (test_coach_can_add_athlete)
- Don't push code that breaks existing tests